-- Store the last motion command
local current_motion = ""

-- Function to update the current motion
function _G.update_motion()
  local mode = vim.fn.mode()
  
  if mode == "n" or mode == "v" then
    -- Update the motion with what you're typing
    current_motion = vim.fn.visualmode() == "" and vim.fn.getcmdline() or vim.fn.visualmode()
  elseif mode == "o" then
    -- Handle operator-pending motions like "d2j"
    current_motion = vim.fn.getcmdline()
  end
end

-- Automatically update the motion on mode changes
vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd({"ModeChanged", "InsertEnter", "TextChanged"}, {
  callback = update_motion
})

local function show_motion()
  local current_mode = vim.fn.mode()

  -- If in normal mode or operator-pending mode, show the motion command
  if current_mode == 'n' or current_mode == 'v' or current_mode == 'x' then
    return vim.fn.getcmdline()  -- Shows current typed motions like 'dw', '2j', etc.
  else
    return ''
  end
end

function()
        -- Show command-motions like dw, 2j, etc.
        local command = vim.fn.getcmdline() -- Gets the command you're typing
        if #command > 0 then
          return command
        end
        return ''
      end

The above command creates a nohup process of clipse --listen-shell, which if called on its own will start a listener in your current terminal session instead. If nohup is not supported on your system, you can use your preferred method of running clipse --listen-shell in the background instead.

Note: The following examples are based on bash/zsh shell environments. If you use something else like foot or fish, you may need to construct the command differently, referencing the relevant documentation.
